items.abstract: <jats:p>Cooling curves were determined for ordinary chondrites within the time- and temperature intervals from ~4.6 to ~4.1 × 10<jats:sup>9</jats:sup>years and ~1400 K to 300 K respectively. This was done by analyzing the 244-plutonium fission track record in whitlockite and adjacent mineral track detectors. The resulting cooling rates constrain the sizes of the parent asteroids to ~120 - 200 km in radius. These dimensions together with the fact that chondrites had never been molten, suggest lower<jats:sup>26</jats:sup>Al/<jats:sup>27</jats:sup>Al initial ratios for ordinary chondritic than for Allende refractory materials.</jats:p>
